    • Constructor Detail

      • VectorLayer

        public VectorLayer(String name,
                   String path,
                   QGisConstants.geometryType geometryType,
                   boolean useHeader)
        Instantiates a new qgis layer that contains vector data (can still be geometry OR data). After calling the constructor you have to:

        # Case 1: shp input file (and in general)

        1) Specify a renderer (how a layer is drawn)

        # Case 2: csv input and geometry

        2) set an x and y field (to tell QGis where the geometry information is stored)

        Optionally: set character that delimits text fields (but causes problems if your lines end on a delimiter)

        If the csv file contains data used for a vector join, no x and y fields need to be specified
        Parameters:
        name - layer name name of the layer (representation in qgis layer tree)
        path - path to the input file
        geometryType - type of geometry within the file
        useHeader -

      • addVectorJoin

        public void addVectorJoin(QGisLayer layer,
                          String joinFieldName,
                          String targetFieldName,
                          String zField)
        Creates a vector join between a geometry layer (e.g. points) and a data layer (e.g. accessibility data, immissions,...). This method must be called by the geometry layer because the vector joins are stored there. You need to specify the name of the data layer and the field names of the geometry and the data layer so QGis can merge objects with same field contents (e.g. same Id). The field names of the layers don't have to be equal.
        Parameters:
        layer - the layer that contains the data (not the geometry)
        joinFieldName - attribute name of the data layer
        targetFieldName - attribute name of the geometry layer
        zField -
